rate, which was, I think, around
12%, because most of his income

00:42:06.760 --> 00:42:10.560
is obviously from capital
and securities and investment

00:42:10.560 --> 00:42:12.070
income.

00:42:12.070 --> 00:42:13.690
If you're a steel
worker in Pittsburgh

00:42:13.690 --> 00:42:17.762
and you pay 25% or 30%, it's
obviously pretty disturbing.

00:42:17.762 --> 00:42:19.470
So what do you think
should governments--

00:42:19.470 --> 00:42:22.970
my question is, how do
you think governments

00:42:22.970 --> 00:42:28.475
should tax capital income
versus income from labor?

00:42:35.172 --> 00:42:37.590
JOHN KAY: I think what's
wrong in the United States

00:42:37.590 --> 00:42:41.440
there is-- and I suspect
the main reason Romney paid

00:42:41.440 --> 00:42:45.920
as little tax as he
does is not actually

00:42:45.920 --> 00:42:48.260
to do with lower tax
rates on capital income

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:50.590
than on labor income,
but to do with the fact

00:42:50.590 --> 00:42:56.490
that there are many more devices
for avoiding tax in the capital

00:42:56.490 --> 00:43:01.100
income sphere than there are
in the labor income sphere.

00:43:01.100 --> 00:43:03.460
And I would like to do
quite a lot about that.

00:43:05.990 --> 00:43:08.500
I think I probably
should stop there

00:43:08.500 --> 00:43:11.390
in terms of talking about
this particular issue

00:43:11.390 --> 00:43:12.592
in this particular building.

00:43:12.592 --> 00:43:14.038
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:15.490 --> 00:43:16.545
AUDIENCE: Fair point.

00:43:16.545 --> 00:43:19.275
ROB LEWORTHY: Last
question then.

00:43:19.275 --> 00:43:21.800
AUDIENCE: So I suppose,
I think, it's clear

00:43:21.800 --> 00:43:23.610
that there's lots
of things wrong

00:43:23.610 --> 00:43:25.610
and that you'd like to
change and lots of people

00:43:25.610 --> 00:43:26.484
would like to change.

00:43:26.484 --> 00:43:31.390
But as you alluded to, there's
not the political strength

00:43:31.390 --> 00:43:33.170
to do them, partly
because there's

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:37.390
so much money in the city
and in Wall Street that stops

00:43:37.390 --> 00:43:38.900
politicians from doing that.

00:43:38.900 --> 00:43:40.760
And I suppose that
strength would have

00:43:40.760 --> 00:43:43.220
to come from us, the people.

00:43:43.220 --> 00:43:46.120
So I wonder, is
there a need for us

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:49.960
to be educated, like
Rob said, to demand that

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:50.860
from our politicians?

00:43:50.860 --> 00:43:53.318
Because otherwise I feel like
that asymmetry of information

00:43:53.318 --> 00:43:55.030
of bankers saying,
we know what's

00:43:55.030 --> 00:43:58.380
best, don't get involved, will
stop us from ever changing.

00:43:58.380 --> 00:44:00.326
So do you think that's
the reason we need--

00:44:00.326 --> 00:44:00.950
JOHN KAY: Yeah.

00:44:00.950 --> 00:44:03.640
I think you're right, when we
have a load of this unfocused,

00:44:03.640 --> 00:44:05.500
as it were, public anger.

00:44:05.500 --> 00:44:09.110
I remember going to
St Paul's churchyard

00:44:09.110 --> 00:44:11.480
when the Occupy
people were in it.

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:13.480
And I saw a sign--
a banner-- saying,

00:44:13.480 --> 00:44:15.372
ban high-frequency trading.

00:44:15.372 --> 00:44:16.830
And I thought, ha,
at least there's

00:44:16.830 --> 00:44:20.540
somebody here who knows
what he's talking about.

00:44:20.540 --> 00:44:22.440
But it turned out
that there was nobody

00:44:22.440 --> 00:44:25.830
who knew what the banner was
about actually in St Paul's

00:44:25.830 --> 00:44:26.750
churchyard.

00:44:26.750 --> 00:44:30.330
So we actually have
to give some focus

00:44:30.330 --> 00:44:32.390
to that particular activity.

00:44:32.390 --> 00:44:40.680
And the big fear I have is that
if democratic politicians can't

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:44.620
give a focus and a channel to
that public anger, what we get

00:44:44.620 --> 00:44:46.870
is what we're seeing
at the moment, which

00:44:46.870 --> 00:44:51.310
is people who will support
crazy guys from whatever parts

00:44:51.310 --> 00:44:56.650
of the political spectrum
whose main attribute

00:44:56.650 --> 00:44:58.470
and the only thing
they have in common

00:44:58.470 --> 00:45:02.980
is that they don't look like
conventional politicians.

00:45:02.980 --> 00:45:06.590
So in a way the rise of Donald
Trump in the United States

00:45:06.590 --> 00:45:08.870
and Jeremy Corbyn
in this country--

00:45:08.870 --> 00:45:12.720
although they could hardly be
more different individuals--

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:15.150
are different aspects
of the same phenomenon.

00:45:15.150 --> 00:45:17.620
And I think it's a very
disturbing phenomenon

00:45:17.620 --> 00:45:19.430
and one where it
is likely to end--

00:45:19.430 --> 00:45:22.290
may end up as it has
ended up before with some

00:45:22.290 --> 00:45:26.750
of these crazy guys
actually taking power.

00:45:26.750 --> 00:45:30.380
That's what we need to avoid
in order to stop ending things

00:45:30.380 --> 00:45:31.850
on a really depressing note.

00:45:31.850 --> 00:45:33.500
ROB LEWORTHY: Please join
me in thanking John Kay.

00:45:33.500 --> 00:45:34.500
Thank you so much, John.

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:36.644
[APPLAUSE]

